SQUIRREL BRAINS, SOURCE OF INFECTIOUS AGENT? (02)
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
[see
CJD & Squirrel Brain Consumption - USA 970901152535
Squirrel brains, source of infectious agent? 970902113214]
[1]
Date: Tue, 2 Sep 1997 18:10:50 +0100
From: O. Hotz de Baar <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>
Just a small reminder that the expected number of CJD cases in the US should
be (and probably is) some 250 per year. Collecting cases for "squirrel brain
eaters" over several years (perhaps effectively over 10 yrs) gives you circa
2500 cases in total. If consumption is rather more common than one might
expect (i.e., a lot of hunters do it) then these numbers may be nothing more
than chance.
On the continent of Europe consuming brains is very common and often regarded
as a delicacy. Indeed my grandmother always gave her young (city-bred)
grandchildren pig's brains on toast as a pick-me-up when they arrived after
the long journey. She got this from her French grandmother. They looked
(ugh!) dreadful, but actually tasted delicious (refusal was not an option,
believe me). Probably full of essential fatty acids too. Anyway, there
doesn't appear to be any greater incidence of CJD in Europe, than in the US.
One should be cautious of jumping [hopping?] to conclusions.
Also a reminder that, at least in the UK, squirrels are known to eat birds
eggs. It might be wrong to assume they are exclusively vegetarian, most
rodents seem to be happy to eat any meat they come across.
--
O. Hotz de Baar
Farmer,
Southern England, UK
e-mail: <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>
